node.title: Tasmania tweaks border plan to scrap pre-travel COVID tests from 'low-risk' states
node.alt: A grey sphere with red and orange blotches.
node.description: Fully vaccinated travellers from low-risk areas will not have to provide a negative COVID-19 test when entering Tasmania under the state's December 15 border reopening plan, Premier Peter Gutwein announces.
node.content: ["Fully vaccinated travellers from low-risk areas will not have to\u00a0provide a negative COVID-19 test when entering Tasmania under a tweak to the state's December 15 border reopening plan, Premier Peter Gutwein has announced.", "In a change to the plan that will see Tasmania reopen to COVID hotspots, the 72-hour pre-travel testing\u00a0requirement will not be needed for some states, but it will remain in place for high-risk areas such as Victoria, New South Wales and the ACT.", "The states that Tasmania currently considers\u00a0low risk are: Queensland, South Australia, Western Australia and the Northern Territory.", "At the moment, travellers from low-risk states do not need a pre-travel COVID test when coming to Tasmania, but the requirement\u00a0was set to come in place after December 15.", "Mr Gutwein also said the state had hit\u00a0a \"significant\" vaccination milestone, with 90 per cent of Tasmanians aged 16 and over having had one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine.", "He said the state was \"very well placed\" to hit its vaccination target of 90 per cent fully vaccinated by early December.", "More to come."]
